{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b7b66c6-fc52-45e5-bf1c-82ef68388822","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) container image instead.\n- For **production**, prefer `dotnet-monitor` as it exposes an HTTP API for on-demand trace collection without exec-ing in.\n- `--duration` keeps the trace bounded — important in a pod where disk is limited.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fe6d4ca5-aca9-4dda-b1d2-c4e09ce1fabe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":426,"requestId":"AC00:2F2B7:146265D:16CF817:6A067110"},"id":"c2f540b3-89ef-4629-bb69-5ba804357368","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:04:26.195Z","parentId":"414a54f6-f6fc-46d3-b534-a2268c671abd"}
